Janma Nakshatram
First of all, each one should know about his/her birth star.

What should one do on Janma Nakshatra day? What not to do? Our ancestors have laid down that.

On the day of one's birth star, marriage, seemantham, ear piercing, hair dying, oil bath, taking medicines, surgery, conjugal relations should not be celebrated.

Instead, you have to do other auspicious things. That is, family deity worship, ishta deity worship, annadanam, charity, taking office, buying property etc. can be done. Janma Nakshtra day is considered to be the most auspicious day fot temple worship.

If a person continues to worship Janma Nakshatra, his eyesight will not come near him. There will be victory in all obstacles. it is good to perform special pujas and abhishek to the presiding deity in temples on Janma star day according to one's capacity. Those who can afford to perform Homa worship on Janma star day can get additonal benefits.

It is the law of the universe that any deity must be blessed by the worship done on the day of Janma Nakshatra.

Especially, if you know which is the supreme deity of Janma Nakshatra Tithi, you can get 100 out of 100 success.

If one worships Lord Shiva on the Tiruvadhirai star day and starts medical treatment, any disease will be cured soon.

Devotees light lamps to Lord Kalabhairava on the Sathayam star day for relief from body pains.

Devotees worship Lord Chitragupta in Kancheepuram on Ashwini, Magam and Moola star days.

Ashiwini

The twins Ashwini Devas are the supreme deities of Ashwini nakshatra. Both of them should be worshipped as having one face, white complexion, two hands holding an amudha kalasam and sitting on a horse carriage. The ritual of Ashwini star is to offer sandalwood paste with black neithal (neelothphala flower), offer incense with saffron, offer cow's milk and laddoos and offer balidanam with suagar pongal. Thus from Avahana to Annabali the rules of the Shanti Yajna are to perform charity and viprabhojana. Thus the objects of other stars and the appropriate mantras are called star shanti.

Krittika

Lord Agnideva, the supreme deity of Krittika star, should be meditated and worshipped as having twi faces, quadrupeds and four horns, holding Sruk, Swara, Abhaya and Varadha on his four hands-seated on a goat vehicle. Jasmine flower with red sandalwood, encense of ghee, sesame seeds, homa thiravyam, urad rice, nivedhana and payasa anna ulundu sadha bali should be offered.

Rohini

Prajapati, the deity of Rohini Star, should be worshipped with four faces, quadrupedsand white in complexion - with axis, kamandalam, abhaya and boon. Lotus flowers, encense of gravel wood, ghee, grains and homa thiravyam, milk annam, suddhannam nivedhanam and payasam and sweet rice should be offered.

Mrigashiram

Somadeva (Moon), the deity of Mrigashirsha star, holding a boon and a staff in His two hands, white in complexion, seated on a chariot drawn by ten horses, is worthy of meditation and worship. Pooja Items- Kumudam (lily), Utbalam (black weaving) flowers; Dasanga Dhoopa; Payasam, Athirasam Nivedyam; Lentils, sesame, pancha kavyam, honey homa perfumes; Sacrifice with lentils and sesame seeds.

Thiruvathirai

Sri Rudra is the presiding deity of Aardra nakshatra. He should be meditated and worshipped with one face, three eyes, white complexion, garlanded with white flowers, holding trident, sword, abhaya and boon in His four hands, seated on a white bull. Fragrant red flowers, golden oomatham flower, yellow sarakondrai flower, tiger clawed kondai, vilwa flower, with special flowers, agaru incense; Ghee, jaggery, lentil payasam, honey nivedhana; Nama Sambhave, the Veda Mantra Japam; Honey and ghee; Sweet Pongal, Payasannam Balidhanam.

Punarpoosam

The Punarvasu star goddess is Aditi Devi, the Mother of Gods. The Goddess is yellow; She holds the Homa Sadhana called Sruk and Swara and the Tarpa or Akshala and Kamandalam in Her two hands. The method of meditation and worship as a benefactor. Jasmine; Malayajadravya Dhoopam; Sandalwood paste mixed with turmeric and saffron, pepper cumin ghee rice; Japa with the Vedic mantra Athitir Dyaur; Homam; Rice mixed with ghee; Sacrifice with swan with turmeric and sandalwood.

Pusham

The Pushya star deity is Jupiter Jupiter and Brihaspati. He should be worshipped in human form, wearing all ornaments – with Yogadanda, Kamandalam or Abhaya and Varada Kaimudra – as the minister and Guru of the celestials. Jasmine, saffron, sandalwood, jasmine, white lotus flowers; Incense with white frankincense; Lotus Thread Torch; Powdered rice porridge mixed with honey and sugar; Samit; Ghee, rice payasam homa trayavam; Sandalwood and flowers with non-woven sacrifice.

Ayilyam

The Ayilya star deity is Nagadeva, the king of snakes. He should be worshipped with a broad photographed snake head, red-skinned, three-eyed, holding a sword and shield board in both hands, wearing yellow clothes, meditating and surrounded by snakes. Karagil sandalwood, blue flower, lavender flower,

Magha

The deities of Magha star are the Pitris. They should be worshipped with one face, two hands, holding the Anna Pinda (a ball of food given to the dead) in the right hand, thin, skinny and bony human body, black as smoke, very holy and benevolent to us. Sandalwood, shenbaga; Gungulian powder; Neyvilakku; Ghee, jaggery appam nivedhana; Mantra Pithumnastosham; Sesame seeds mixed with ghee and honey; Raw rice, banyan tree shoots, homa thiravyams; Sacrifice with black sesame seeds.

Pooram

Aryama, the goddess of the Poora star. One should be worshipped with one face, two hands, black body like smoke, holding a Shakti weapon in his hand and sitting on a chariot. Sandalwood, Malathi Jasmine, Porasam flower; Vilvakkai sawdust incense; Ghee rice, athirasam, laddu, nivedhanam; Japa homam by the mantra Aryamanam Devam ; Ghee-mixed millet Homa Thiravyam; Offering to the Sun Aryama with sandalwood flowers, Sweet Pongal.

Uthiram

Uttara star deity Bhagadeva. He holds a conch and chakra in both hands and is seated on a good chariot. He is also the one who gives the desired benefit of the devotees and is worthy of meditation and worship. He is worshipped with sandal paste and white flowers. Mix ghee with bilva fruit and kungulium and incense them; Offering sesame seeds; Chant the Aasathye Neti Mantra; Sesame, mustard and paddy should be offered as homa thiruviyam and samba rice should be offered as a sacrifice.

Hast

Savita (Sun), the goddess of Hasta star, should be worshipped as the husband of Chayadevi sitting in lotus posture on a chariot with seven horses. Adorned with sandalwood, lotus and red colored alari; Burn incense with sandalwood and frankincense; Ghee payasam, jaggery appam; Chant the mantra Ududyam Jatavedasa; Offering Ahuthis in homa with curd, ghee and rice; Annabali (kesari) with sandalwood flower, illuppai flower, arugu, sesame seeds, ghee and jaggery should be offered.

Chithirai

Savita (Sun), the goddess of Hasta star, should be worshipped as the husband of Chayadevi sitting in lotus posture on a chariot with seven horses. Adorned with sandalwood, lotus and red colored alari; Burn incense with sandalwood and frankincense; Ghee payasam, jaggery appam; Chant the mantra Ududyam Jatavedasa; Offering Ahuthis in homa with curd, ghee and rice; Annabali (kesari) with sandalwood flower, illuppai flower, arugu, sesame seeds, ghee and jaggery should be offered.

Swathi

This star deity is Vayu Dev. He should be worshipped as seated on a deer, of smoke complexion, holding a sword and shield in both hands. He should be worshipped with Karakil sandalwood paste, Marikozhundhal, incense with white Akil wood powder, offering curd and curd, chanting the mantra 'Sanapitaa', Ahuthi in homa with ghee, Yavai grain and Payasanna, offering sacrifice with sandal flower and Swati star Shanthi properly.

Visakam

These star deities, Indra and Agni, are the givers of auspiciousness, with two hands with the mudras of abhaya and varada. Both of them should be worshipped with lotus flower and bandhuka flowers with sandalwood, incense with deodar wood powder, nivedhana with payasam mixed with ghee, chant with the mantra 'Samna Indraagni', ghee paalanna ahuthi and milk rice bali with skanda pushpam.

Anusham

Meditate and worship Mithradeva, the goddess of Anuradha star, sitting in lotus posture, holding a trident and ankusa in both hands. He should be worshipped with white lotus flower, incense with sandal paste, offered gheepayasam, chanted with the mantra 'Mitrasya sarshaneetrutha', performed homa and propitiated with soornaganda.

Kettai

Worship Lord Indra, the deity of Jyeshtha star, seated on an elephant called Airavatha, as a quadrangular person with thunderbolt, affection, boon and abhaya. He should be worshipped with sandal paste with lotus and Patoli flowers, incense with green camphor and Akhil wood powder, Chitrannam nivedi, chant and homa with the mantra 'Indram Vo', offer ahuthi of sweet potato, root and sacrifice with curd with sandalwood flowers.

Source

Worship Nirrutideva, the goddess of the original star, as one face with a fierce mouth, dark blue complexion, the leader of the Rakshasa clan, with upward shaved hair, and red and round eyes. He should be worshipped with karagil (and goathorn powder) incense, blue buffalo flower with karagil sandalwood, marigolds, red Ashoka flower, black neithal flower, black gram rice (fish, meat, toddy, etc.) and chant with the mantra 'Moshuna: Parapara' and offer sacrifice to Niruthi and pacify him.

Pooradam

Purvashadā (Purva Shada) or Poorada star deity (Apa: water) should be worshipped in the form of waves on the ocean as the protector of all living beings and as the giver of auspiciousness every day. They should be worshipped with the black neithal flower called Kalhara, incense the mind with mineral powder, rice porridge mixed with curd, chant with the mantra 'Abohishta', Ahuthi with red paddy, offer cumin rice and payasannam.

Uthiradam

Vishve Devas are the deities of Uttarashada or Uttara Nakshatra. Let us worship the Vishve Devas who bestow beauty, prosperity, fame and knowledge to wash away all sins. They should be worshipped with five flowers, agaru incense with lacquer, five types of Pakshana nivedhana, chant the mantra "Vishve devasa agathe", offer dravyahuthi with ghee and balidanam with payasannam.

Abhijit

The deity of the star Abhijit is Lord Brahma who emerges from the navel of Tirumal and recites the Vedas. He should be worshipped in lotus posture with four faces and four hands – holding Theertha Kandika, Akshamala, Veda book and lotus flower in His four hands. Instead of doing the santhi of this star alone, one should worship the next Tirumal with the Tiruvonam star and have peace with the homadanathis.

Thiruvonam

Lord Vishnu, the deity of the star Srona known as Tiruvonam, has a calm appearance, two huge eyes like lotus petals, four hands holding conch, chakra, abhaya, boon and a blue complexion, and is worshipped as sitting on the Garuda vehicle. He is propitiated with lotus and jasmine flowers with sandalwood, Dasanka Thiraviya powder with incense, ghee, milk, sugar porridge or ghee with Payasanna nivedhana with the mantra "Adho Deva", Dravyahuthi with red rice and finally Annabali for Lord Vishnu with sandal flower.

Avittam

The eight deities of the Avitta star called Shravishta should be worshipped as Ashtavasus, who are crowned on a chariot and have fingerprints in the form of a conch shell and a wheel. They should offer puja with eight petals of lotus flower with 100 petals, incense with Kungulium, nivedhana with payasam and neypoli sweets, Ahuthi with arasu, vilwa and fig, and Thrayanthamiha deva with ghee-mixed lentil rice balidhana.

Sadayam

It is customary to worship Varunadeva, the deity of Sadhaya star known as Satabhishak, holding an amudha kalasam and affection in His two hands, white complexion and worshipped by the celestials. He should be worshipped with lotus and other water flowers, incense with Dasanga, offering ghee payasam and rice porridge, chanting the mantra "Imam me Varuna", Ahuthi with the things that appear in the water, offering sacrifice with payasannam.

Poorattathi

Ajar is the Purva Proshtapada or Purva bhadrapad star deity. (Bhairava of Mahapralaya period). He should be worshipped as having only one leg, who is eternally invisible, who is worshipped by all the demigods, and as Rudramurthi of the Samhara period. He should be worshipped with buffalo and ferry flowers, offered incense with herbs, offered curd mixed with ghee and honey, Ahuthi with a piece of pumpkin dipped in ghee, sacrificed with ghee rice and pacified.

Uthirattadhi

Meditate and worship Uttarabhadra or Uttara Dati star deity Ahirputniya, crowned with conch shell and discus. He should be worshipped with Karanji (Vishnu Kranti) Bhadram, offered ghee, Sweet Pongal offerings, Ahuthi with ghee with black gram and lentil grains, offered ghee jaggery rice and pacified him.

Revathi

Pusha is the deity of Revati nakshatra. He has one face, two legs, boon and abhaya in both hands and is worshipped on a jewelled throne. He should be worshipped with Mandhara flower, offered Kunguliya incense with red sandalwood, offered sesame seeds, rice, jaggery powder, Ahuthi with ghee with banana or mango and sacrificed with payasannam.
